Next, we measured bacterial viability by live/dead bacterial fluorescence staining and flow cytometry to assess the in vitro photokilling performance of SN@CNDs. The green fluorescence of the dark group of SN@CNDs proved that it had no significant bactericidal performance as the control groups. In the NIR groups, S@CNDs and N@CNDs showed a slight red fluorescence signal, indicating that they had weak antimicrobial photokilling effects. However, the SN@CNDs group showed much more red fluorescence (62.3%) than the control group (less than 10%), fully confirming the better in vitro antimicrobial photokilling performance of SN@CNDs compared with S@CNDs and N@CNDs (Fig. 4
                        (a)-(h) and Fig. 5
                        ). In addition, similar results were observed in bacterial standard plate colony counts and growth curves. As shown in Fig. 4(i)–(q), the survival and growth rate of bacteria treated with SN@CNDs and NIR irradiation were much lower than those of PBS, S@CNDs, and N@CNDs. Moreover, the photokilling effect of SN@CNDs increased significantly with increasing concentration, and the bactericidal rate was as high as 99.99% when the concentration reached 200 μg/mL (Fig. S2). These results suggest that SN@CNDs have a concentration-dependent photokilling effect on VRE-resistant bacteria.
